Suetonius of necessity reflecte the literary tendencies of his time; yet his style is less typical of the Silver Age than that of any other writer of the period. His use of Greek words and poetical phrases and constructione seems to be due to the influence of the age rather than to his personal inclination. The brevity oi Suetonius’ diction is not epi· grammatic, nor employed with erident artistic purpose. It is the brevity of economy, which aims to express the thought in the simplest and fewest words. N eglect of concinnity and parallelism of construction, while not carried toercess as in Tacitus, are peculiarities of Suetonius’ style. The sentences are comparatively short, and there is an entire absence of the periodie structure. As would he expected from these truite, his prose is not harmonious. In fact, he seems to be utterly lacking in a feeling for rhythm. He does not strive for effect, and his diction is singularly free from rhetorical ornamentation. He keeps himself entirely out of his works, , with the result that his style is somewhat colorless. Its very simplicity, however, gives an element of strength and vigor.
